# Requirements Traceability Matrix

**Project:** Privacy-Preserving File Transfer Platform
**Module:** COM668 — Computing Project
**Student:** Vishnu Vekaria (B00969091)
**Source:** AT2 Challenge Definition Report — Section 3.1

---

## How to Use This Matrix

As each requirement is implemented, fill in:
- **File(s)** — the source file(s) where it is implemented
- **Function(s)** — the specific function(s) that satisfy it
- **Test** — how it was verified against the acceptance criterion
- **Status** — current implementation status

---

## Functional Requirements

| ID | Requirement | MoSCoW | Acceptance Criterion | File(s) | Function(s) | Test | Status |
|----|-------------|--------|----------------------|---------|-------------|------|--------|
| FR1 | Allow users to register and authenticate securely | Must | Valid credentials allow login. Invalid or duplicate credentials are rejected with an error message. | | | | 🔴 Not started |
| FR2 | Hash passwords prior to storage | Must | No plaintext password exists in any database record or log. Only bcrypt hash values are stored. | | | | 🔴 Not started |
| FR3 | Encrypt file content on the client side before upload | Must | Outgoing HTTP request payload contains only ciphertext. No plaintext file data reaches the server at any point during upload. | | | | 🔴 Not started |
| FR4 | Ensure encryption keys are generated client-side and never stored in plaintext on the server | Must | No plaintext keys exist in server storage or logs. Key generation occurs in the browser session only. Only the IV is transmitted. | | | | 🔴 Not started |
| FR5 | Store encrypted file content without accessing plaintext data | Must | All server-stored files are unreadable ciphertext. Decryption is only possible client-side using the retained key. | | | | 🔴 Not started |
| FR6 | Log structured metadata including encrypted file size, timestamp, and transfer frequency | Must | Each upload produces a metadata record within one second containing size, timestamp, and frequency. No filename is stored. | | | | 🔴 Not started |
| FR7 | Compute anomaly scores using Z-score methodology | Must | System Z-score matches manual calculation of Z = (x − μ) / σ within floating-point tolerance. | | | | 🔴 Not started |
| FR8 | Compute anomaly thresholds using the IQR method | Must | System correctly computes Q1, Q3, IQR and boundary values matching manually verified results. | | | | 🔴 Not started |
| FR9 | Flag metadata entries exceeding defined statistical thresholds | Must | Records exceeding thresholds are flagged TRUE with timestamp. Records within bounds remain unflagged. | | | | 🔴 Not started |
| FR10 | Store anomaly detection results for review and evaluation | Must | Each detection event produces a persisted result linked to MetadataID, queryable by user and time range. | | | | 🔴 Not started |
| FR11 | Display aggregate usage statistics and detected anomalies via a dashboard | Should | Dashboard loads within three seconds and correctly displays uploads, size distribution, anomaly count, and recent events. | | | | 🔴 Not started |

---

## Non-Functional Requirements

| ID | Category | Requirement | Acceptance Criterion | File(s) | Implementation Notes | Test | Status |
|----|----------|-------------|----------------------|---------|----------------------|------|--------|
| NFR1 | Security | File content must remain confidential through client-side encryption. Communication must use TLS. Passwords must be hashed using a secure algorithm. | Network inspection confirms all communication occurs over HTTPS. No plaintext file content, passwords, or keys are present in server-side storage or logs. | | | | 🔴 Not started |
| NFR2 | Performance | Encryption operations must complete within acceptable latency for typical file sizes. Anomaly detection must execute efficiently on structured metadata. | Client-side encryption of a 10MB file completes within five seconds. Anomaly score computation for a single metadata record completes within one second. | | | | 🔴 Not started |
| NFR3 | Reliability | Metadata integrity must be preserved during storage. Encrypted files must remain retrievable and decryptable after upload. | A file uploaded and subsequently downloaded decrypts correctly to its original content in all test cases. | | | | 🔴 Not started |
| NFR4 | Usability | The dashboard must present anomaly results clearly and interpretably. | A test user can correctly identify the number of flagged anomalies and the most recent flagged event within two minutes, without assistance. | | | | 🔴 Not started |
| NFR5 | Scalability | The system must support small-scale organisational usage within defined constraints. | The system handles ten concurrent users performing simultaneous uploads without errors or measurable degradation. | | | | 🔴 Not started |

---

## Stakeholder → Requirements Mapping

| Stakeholder | Primary Needs | Requirements Driven |
|-------------|---------------|---------------------|
| End Users (file senders and recipients) | Client-side encryption, secure auth, usable UI | FR1, FR2, FR3, FR4, FR5 |
| Security Administrators | Anomaly detection, dashboard visibility | FR6, FR7, FR8, FR9, FR10, FR11 |
| Deploying Organisations | GDPR compliance, data minimisation, reliability | NFR1, NFR2, NFR3, NFR4, NFR5 |

